We have 12 numeric variables. The summary shows max really far out for residual.sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur, density Those might be outlier/reporting problem or really special wines.

Quality

First of all, what about quality of those red wines Also, quality is a numeric, we will add it as a factor.

It looks like a normal distribution. Notes are out of 10. Most of the wines are around 5/6. My main line of inquiries will be the relation between all variables to quality. Looking at alcohol:

Much more disparate but we have a nice peak around 9.5 Does alcohol level affects the quality?

## [1] 0.4761663

There is a medium correlation between quality and alcohol, the graph shows that the higher the quality, the higher the alcohol. This is especially true for the higher end wines.

Acidity variables

We have 3 types of acidity listed:

  • Fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)
  • Volatile acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar tast
  • Citric acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add freshness and flavor to wines

They should all relate to the ph I think.

#fixed pH and fixed acidity correlation
cor(red_wines$pH, red_wines$fixed.acidity)
## [1] -0.6829782
#fixed pH and volatile acidity correlation
cor(red_wines$pH, red_wines$volatile.acidity)
## [1] 0.2349373
#fixed pH and citric acid correlation
cor(red_wines$pH, red_wines$citric.acid)
## [1] -0.5419041

So Fixed acidity and citric acid correlate quite strongly with the pH, but not the volatile acidity.

Volatile acidity and pH are not related. Even for high quality wines, the pH seems to vary greatly.

Quality and pH

Lets get a closer look between those pH and quality now.

The higher the quality, the lower the pH it seems. What about salt?

Getting a taste

Lets try multi-variables plots to see if we can have a better picture.

Chlorides and alcohol by quality

The overall trend is downward: less chlorides as the alcohol level gets higher. But we can see that for the top 2 qualities, we got a rebound around 12 where salt level rises a bit. It might be some outlier as we only got a few points for those quality.

with(subset(red_wines, quality.lvl==5),cor(chlorides,alcohol))

Furthermore, we have very far off values in both residual.sugar and chlorides, lets calculate the same value on a subset limited between the .05 and .95 quantiles.

red_wines_quant<-subset(red_wines,
                        quantile(red_wines$residual.sugar,0.05)<=residual.sugar
                        & quantile(red_wines$residual.sugar,0.95)>=residual.sugar
                        & quantile(red_wines$chlorides,0.05)<=chlorides 
                        & quantile(red_wines$chlorides,0.95)>=chlorides)

with(subset(red_wines_quant, quality.lvl==5),
     cor(residual.sugar, chlorides))

Acidity variables and quality

Lets go back to our acidity variables:

We can see that fixed acidity is not really relevant to quality, but volatile.acidity and citric acid are. The higher the citric acid level, the better the quality. The relation between volatile acidity and quality is the other way around. Futhermore, looking at the median we can see some group of qualities: 3 & 4, 5 & 6 and 7 & 8.

with(red_wines, cor(quality, fixed.acidity))
## [1] 0.1240516
with(red_wines, cor(quality, volatile.acidity))
## [1] -0.3905578
with(red_wines, cor(quality, citric.acid))
## [1] 0.2263725

Correlation confirms that fixed acidity correlates only weakly with the quality. On the other hand, volatile acidity and citric acid are much stronger, especially volatile acidity. This kind of acidity correlate negatively with quality meaning that as the quality improves, the volatile acidity decreases.

So we now have alcohol, citric acid and volatile acidity correlating quite strongly with quality. I will get back to the previous facetted chart of residual sugar and chlorides and add citric acid/volatile acidity to see if I can get some more information.

Final Plots and Summary

First of all, there are outliers in the dataset. I tried to remove them when their value seemed to really be out of range. But it might also underlines the diversity of wines. As I am not sure, the following graphs are based on the whole dataset. All in all, there is not some really strong correlations between quality and the other variables presented here. But I could understood some relationships regarding tastes:

Vinegar taste is not really looked for

The density were scaled so that the low counts of the extreme quality do affect the overall distribution. As the quality of the wines get higher, the volatile acidity is getting lower. It is not always true. This is kind of what we can expect. When you buy cheap wine (which is not always, but most of the time of lower quality) it has most of the tume a pugent smell and taste, like vinegar.

But citric acid is the other way around

This kind of acid add freshness and flavor. It is confirmed by the boxplot: lower quality wines have less citric acid in general than their higher contourparts. We can group quality into 3 supra group:

  1. Quality 3 & 4: low citric acid median at 0.08
  2. Quality 5 & 6: median around 0.24
  3. Quality 7 & 8: median around 0.4

Get high alcohol level and high sulphates for better wines

This graph shows smoothers of alcohol by sulphates for all quality. The low quality (3) wines vary a lot but the overal trend is that they are high in alcohol with low sulphates and the alcohol level decreases as the sulphates level increases. Qualities 4 to 7 are flat overall and the only differences come from the alcohol level. Quality 8 wines are peculiar in that they are grouped in the top right corner. The relationship is not flat like the other quality (except 3) but those wines have more alcohol and more sulphates.

Reflection

I started the analysis by looking at the data overal. Some data points seemed really far out and during the analysis, I removed some of them. But I decided to keep them in the end as wine tastes can vary greatly.
Looking at the different variables, I decidied to investigate what made a wine good. I started by looking at the main things that could affect taste: alcohol, chlorides, residual.sugar and pH. My first finding was really about alcohol and quality.
I then moved to multivariables analyses by combining alcohol with chlorides and residual.sugar. The overall trends by quality looked quite similar so I tried to plot chlorides with residual.sugar. But the results was not what I was expecting. Thinking that another factor might be related with those two, I went through the the acidity variables and the quality to select volatile.acidity and citric.acidity and plot them with chlorides and residual.sugar. The plots seemed to give something for citric.acid byt I was overreading it, the correlation is low. I did the same exercice for the rest of the variables.
I get all in all several variables correlating with quality: * Alcohol * Volatile acidity (negative correlation) * Citric acid * Sulphates I was looking for some more adavanced relations between the variables but was not able to find them. I am especially surprised that residual.sugar and chlorides does not affect quality more.
The limits of the dataset are really the lack of points on the lower and higher quality wines. Futhermore, the source of the quality is unknown, is it from a professionnal? A store? And we have to keep in mind that taste is a really cultural thing (see the indian food analysis) and a good wine for someone might not be for another. Last but not least, we do not have the age of the wine. In France, one of the first thing we check for a wine is its age because common knowledge dictates that an older wine is better than a younger one (for normal year). I would have love to validate or discard this coutume. Another thing that I would like is to get the name of the wines so that I can get their prices and see if how they relate to quality.
